This paper is likely to belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category as it deals with mechanism design and incentive compatibility of agents. It also involves the implementation of social choice functions, which is a common topic in game theory. Additionally, the use of probabilistic verification is related to the concept of Bayesian games, which is a subfield of game theory. 

The paper could also be classified under Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) as it involves designing mechanisms that can handle agents that are not fully rational. 

The use of probabilistic verification and the analysis of the complexity of the mechanisms suggest that this paper could also be classified under Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) and Learning (cs.LG). 

Finally, the paper deals with the issue of misbehaving agents and the imposition of fines, which is related to the sub-category of Cryptography and Security (cs.CR).
